'''Tar-Minastir''' ({{SA|1474}} – {{SA|1873|n}}, aged 399 years) was the eleventh [[King of Númenor]], ruling for 138 years, from {{SA|1731}} to {{SA|1869|n}}.<ref name=Tar-Minastir/>

==History==
Tar-Minastir was the grandson of King [[Tar-Súrion]]. Before becoming King he used the name Minastir. He succeeded his aunt, Queen [[Tar-Telperiën]].<ref name=Tar-Telperien/> He acquired his name Minastir after building a high tower upon the hill of [[Oromet]] near [[Andúnië]] and the west shores of Númenor, to spend time gazing westwards.<ref name=Tar-Minastir/>

During his time, in [[Middle-earth]], the [[War of the Elves and Sauron]] began in {{SA|1693}},<ref>{{App|SA}}, entry for the year 1693, p. 1083</ref> [[Sauron]] invaded [[Eriador]] in {{SA|1695}}<ref>{{App|SA}}, entry for the year 1695, p. 1083</ref> and the realm of [[Eregion]] fell. Sauron then advanced to [[Lindon]] and besieged [[Rivendell]].<ref name=Concerning>{{UT|Concerning}}</ref> Minastir, who loved the Eldar, but envied them,<ref name=Tar-Minastir/> sent a navy under the command of [[Ciryatur]] to Lindon to aid the Elves in {{SA|1700|n}}.<ref name=Tar-Telperien/><ref name=Concerning/><ref name=SA1700>{{App|SA}}, entry for the year 1700, p. 1083</ref><ref>{{UT|5a}}, Note 9</ref><ref>{{NM|P3xviii}}, p. 370</ref><ref group="note">In ''The Tale of Years'' it is stated that "Tar-Minastir", his name with the prefix ''Tar-'' of the King of Númenor, sent a great navy from Númenor to Lindon in {{SA|1700}} (see ''citation 7''). This event and date are restated in ''The History of Galadriel and Celeborn'', mentioning "Tar-Minastir the King" (see ''citation 6''). Yet in ''The Line of Elros'' Tar-Telperiën is said to have lived to {{SA|1731}} and not have given up the sceptre until that time, which would mean she was the ruler of Númenor when the great navy was sent (see ''citation 2''). [[Christopher Tolkien]] could not account for this discrepancy (see ''citation 8''). It is possible to reconcile this discrepancy if Minastir sent the fleet in a capacity, such as [[Regent]] or [[Captain of the King's Ships|Captain of the Queen's Ships]] before he ascended the throne and that later chroniclers simply referred to him as "Tar-" or "the King" without taking into account that he had not taken the sceptre and had not formally become the king when he sent the fleet to Lindon. In a ''Note on the delay of Gil-galad and the Númenóreans'' it is mentioned that the great host of "Minastir" landed in Middle-earth (see ''citation 9'').</ref> Ciryatur's forces utterly routed Sauron's army in the [[Battle of the Gwathló]] and reinforcements from Lindon and [[Tharbad]] helped defeat the enemy. Sauron retreated back to [[Mordor]].<ref name=Concerning/>

The Númenóreans who had tasted power in Middle-earth in the battles with Sauron, began establishing dominions on the coasts of [[Middle-earth]] starting around the year 1800.<ref name="SA">{{App|SA}}, entry for the year ''c.'' 1800, p. 1083</ref>

Tar-Minastir was one of the last "good" Kings of the realm, as his successors started becoming greedy of wealth and power.<ref>{{App|Numenor}}, paragraph following the paragraph about Tar-Minastir, p. 1036</ref>

In 1869<ref name=Tar-Minastir/> his son, [[Tar-Ciryatan]], constrained Tar-Minastir to surrender the sceptre before he would have done of his free will.<ref name=Tar-Ciryatan/>

== Etymology ==
''Minastir'' is a [[Quenya]] name. Its meaning is not glossed, but Paul Strack suggests it might mean "Watch Tower" as a compound of a shortened form ''minas'' of ''minassë'' ("tower"), and a form of ''tir'' ("to watch").<ref>{{webcite|author=Paul Strack|articleurl=https://www.eldamo.org/content/words/word-1070886961.html|articlename=Q. ''Minastir'' m.|website=Eldamo|accessed=22 December 2021}}</ref> Like all the rulers of Númenor who took their royal names in Quenya, Minastir added the prefix ''tar-'' ("high") to his name when he received the [[Sceptre of Númenor|Sceptre]].<ref>{{UT|Kings}}, first paragraph and entry I to XXV</ref>

